    <p><a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a></p>

    <h1>A love let&#xAD;ter to Ire&#xAD;land and lyri&#xAD;cal pas&#xAD;sion</h1>
    <h2>Star&#xAD;ring Emily Blunt and Jamie Dor&#xAD;nan and set in Ire&#xAD;land, Wild Moun&#xAD;tain Thyme fol&#xAD;lows one woman&#x2019;s en&#xAD;dur&#xAD;ing af&#xAD;fec&#xAD;tion for her shy neigh&#xAD;bour</h2>
    <section>
        <time datetime="2021-01-14"><a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210114/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-14">2021-01-14</a></time> -
        Ali&#xAD;son de Souza stlife@sph.com.sg&#xD;&#xA;Wild Moun&#xAD;tain Thyme opens today.

            <a href="/category/tag-268435461/en/sg">Entertainment</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268449470/en/sg">Celebrities</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268449474/en/sg">Movies</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537068151/en/sg">Ireland</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537254310/en/sg">Emily Blunt</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-536891206/en/sg">Singapore</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-538244394/en/sg">Jamie Dornan</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537196092/en/sg">Christopher Walken</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537196963/en/sg">Jon Hamm</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537723054/en/sg">The Edge</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-540475914/en/sg">A Quiet Place</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537266011/en/sg">Mullingar</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537357997/en/sg">The Fall</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-542139741/en/sg">Hollywood</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-540259867/en/sg">Hollywood</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-540559462/en/sg">The Devil Wears Prada</a>     </section>

        <p>In the ro­man­tic drama Wild Moun­tain Thyme, Emily Blunt plays a woman un­apolo­get­i­cally pur­su­ing the man of her dreams – even though he is obliv­i­ous to her af­fec­tions.</p>
        <p>Open­ing in Sin­ga­pore cin­e­mas today, it is writ­ten and di­rected by John Pa­trick Shan­ley, who won a Best Orig­i­nal Screen­play Os­car for the acclaimed ro­man­tic com­edy Moon­struck (1987).</p>
        <p>Blunt plays Rose­mary, who has been in love with the shy and ec­cen­tric An­thony (Jamie Dor­nan) – her neigh­bour in their small Irish farm­ing com­mu­nity – since they were chil­dren.</p>
        <p>But An­thony is un­aware of her feel­ings and is pre­oc­cu­pied with a plan by his fa­ther Tony (Christo­pher Walken) to sell the fam­ily farm. The buyer is a rich Amer­i­can cousin, Adam (Jon Hamm), who be­comes ro­man­ti­cally in­ter­ested in Rose­mary.</p>
        <p>Speak­ing at the film’s vir­tual premiere, Blunt, 37, says she greatly ad­mired her char­ac­ter’s de­ter­mi­na­tion when it comes to love.</p>
        <p>“She re­ally is this lyri­cal ro­man­tic. She is wildly pas­sion­ate and she can’t put one foot in front of the other with­out think­ing of An­thony and how much she wants to be with him,” says the star of The Edge Of To­mor­row (2014) and The Devil Wears Prada (2006).</p>
        <p>“She has such pur­pose and de­ter­mi­na­tion in per­suad­ing him of that. And that’s what I re­ally loved about her, that forth­right knowl­edge of, ‘This is who is meant for me and I’m never giv­ing up.’</p>
        <p>“She’s sort of try­ing to drag him into the next phase of her life and I find her to be a re­ally ex­cit­ing and mod­ern woman,” says the English ac­tress, who also ap­peared in the hit hor­ror film A Quiet Place (2018).</p>
        <p>Shan­ley, 70, adapted the film from his 2014 play, Out­side Mullingar, which draws on his Irish-Amer­i­can roots.</p>
        <p>“The main char­ac­ter of this film is Ire­land, Irish cul­ture and the way the Irish peo­ple use the lan­guage to ex­press thoughts that might be shaped a lit­tle dif­fer­ently than they are with other peo­ple.</p>
        <p>“So it’s kind of a love let­ter to Ire­land,” says the writer, who won a Pulitzer Prize and Tony Award for his 2005 Broad­way drama, Doubt: A Parable.</p>
        <p>Shan­ley’s lyri­cal sen­si­bil­i­ties come through in the film’s unique di­a­logue, says Blunt.</p>
        <p>“John wanted to make this about his fam­ily and grow­ing up in Ire­land, and how peo­ple ex­press them­selves so exquisitel­y there – they’re all poets.</p>
        <p>“The script had this lyri­cism that was so unique yet John writes in a way that’s very grounded. So I was com­pletely be­witched by it,” the ac­tress says.</p>
        <p>It was fit­ting that her love in­ter­est is played by a real Ir­ish­man. Dor­nan is the star of the Fifty Shades Of Grey ro­man­tic films (2015 to 2018) and crime se­ries The Fall (2013 to 2016). But he is not the stan­dard-is­sue Hol­ly­wood hunk, says Blunt – and that made him well suited to this role.</p>
        <p>“There might be a per­cep­tion of Jamie be­cause a lot of peo­ple lust af­ter him. But I think, ac­tu­ally, his char­ac­ter An­thony – in all his awk­ward shy­ness – is much closer to Jamie’s real per­son­al­ity, and so he was re­ally com­fort­able and free in this role.”</p>
        <p>And the mo­ment she and Dor­nan read through the script, she knew “we wanted to make the same film, and that we’d both fallen in love with these strange farm­ers who had been driven mad by their iso­la­tion and lone­li­ness”.</p>
        <p>Dor­nan says his char­ac­ter is not the typ­i­cal ro­man­tic pro­tag­o­nist. “He’s some­one who strug­gles to ex­press him­self and re­ally say what he means,” says the 38-yearold.</p>
        <p>The per­former re­lated to this. “As an ac­tor, you’re al­ways putting on some kind of front, par­tic­u­larly in this in­dus­try, and al­ways hav­ing to show your best self. But it’s kind of ex­haust­ing and it’s not re­al­ity a lot of the time, and I can re­late to some­one be­ing re­ally shy and strug­gling so­cially.”</p>
        <p>Dor­nan adds with a laugh that An­thony is “weird”.</p>
        <p>“I have an odd­ness to me that I don’t get to ex­press very of­ten. And I felt An­thony was this ve­hi­cle to al­low my­self to throw out every od­dity that lives within me and make it phys­i­cal in this char­ac­ter.”</p>

